Package civitas.celestis.math.fraction

Class Fraction

java.lang.Object
civitas.celestis.math.vector.Vector2
civitas.celestis.math.fraction.Fraction
All Implemented Interfaces:
Numeric, Vector, Serializable, Comparable<Fraction>
public class Fraction extends Vector2 implements Comparable<Fraction>
A number which can accurately represent recursion. Non-finite values are not supported as the numerator or denominator.

Fractions are useful for accurately handling the division of two numbers. Unlike other implementations within this project, division by fractions will not immediately throw an ArithmeticException. Instead, the pure form of the numerator and denominator will both be stored as-is.

This is an example on how to perform division using a fraction.
// 1 on 3 division
final Fraction result = new Fraction(1, 3);

// You can either keep this as-is, or convert it to a double
final double value = result.doubleValue();

    • compareTo

      public int compareTo(@Nonnull Fraction f)
      Compares this fraction to the given fraction. The assumption for special values are as follows.
      NOT_A_NUMBER > POSITIVE_INFINITY,
      NOT_A_NUMBER > NEGATIVE_INFINITY,
      POSITIVE_INFINITY > NEGATIVE_INFINITY
      Specified by:
      compareTo in interface Comparable<Fraction>
      Parameters:
      f - The fraction to compare to
      Returns:
      0 if the values are equal, 1 if this fraction is larger, -1 if this fraction is smaller
      See Also:
      • Double.compare(double, double)
